net.akami.mask.merge

Interface Merge<P,R,PROP extends OverallMergeProperty<P,R>>

  • Type Parameters:
    P - the input type used
    R - the result type, might or might not be the same as the input type
    PROP - the type of OverallMergeProperty handled
    All Known Subinterfaces:
    FairMerge<T,PROP>, SequencedMerge<T>, SinglePropertySequencedMerge<T>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    BasicMonomialAdditionMerge, DuplicateEraser, MonomialAdditionMerge, MonomialDivisionMerge, MonomialMultiplicationMerge, PairEraser, VariableCombination

    public interface Merge<P,R,PROP extends OverallMergeProperty<P,R>>
    A behavior that takes two entries of the same type, and outputs a result that may or may not be of the same type.

    Outputs are by default calculated using OverallMergeProperty objects. These properties check one by one whether they can produce a result from the two inputs given, and return this result is suitable. If no property matches the two inputs, an error is automatically thrown.

    If there is only one property that can be applied to any pair of input, use Collections.singletonList(property).

    The merge method takes a boolean in parameter, which defines whether the object is being merged with itself. This is only useful through redefinitions of the #merge(P, P, boolean) method, such as SequencedMerge. If your method is not redefined, the value passed in parameter will not be taken into account.

    Author:
    Antoine Tran
    See Also:
    FairMerge, SequencedMerge

    • Method Detail

      • merge

        default R merge(P p1,
                P p2,
                boolean selfMerge)
        Computes a result from the two input given.

        By default, goes through the different OverallMergeProperty generated by the generateOverallProperties(Object, Object) method, and returns OverallMergeProperty.computeResult() from the first property suiting the two inputs (checked via MergeProperty.isSuitable(). The boolean parameter is only used through redefinitions of this method, see SequencedMerge for a concrete example.

        Parameters:
        p1 - the first input
        p2 - the second input
        selfMerge - whether a single input corresponds to both p1 and p2 parameters
        Returns:
        a computed result from the two inputs given, according to the overall properties (by default)

      • generateOverallProperties

        java.util.List<PROP> generateOverallProperties(P p1,
                                               P p2)
        Generates a list of properties from the given input.

        Every time a merge occurs, a new list of properties must be generated. The reason for that is that these properties might handle different fields that depend on the constructor parameters (the two inputs). Using setters instead of re-instantiating new properties is also not recommended, since a property might recursively use itself, and change the value of the inputs before the end of the calculation of the result. If you are guaranteed that recursive usage will not happen, you might consider adding setters to your properties instead and always return the same list.

        Parameters:
        p1 - the first input
        p2 - the second input
        Returns:
        a list of properties constructed from the two inputs
